e reception of his work by Jewish scholars and readers. The anti-Semitic appropriation of Goethe is additionally discussed.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn German.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2022) 0aAuthors, GermanxBiographyxHistory and criticism. 0aGerman literaturexHistory and criticismxSources. 0aYiddish literaturexInfluence. 4aDeutsch-jüdische Kulturgeschichte. 4aGoethe-Rezeption. 4aNationalismus. 4aZionismus. 7aHISTORY / Jewish.2bisacsh  aGerman-Jewish cultural history.  aGoethe reception.  aZionism.  anationalism.1 aBorchmeyer, Dieter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBreuer, Stefan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBunzel, Wolfgang, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGelhard, Dorothee, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGörner, Rüdiger, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHöhne, Steffen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHöhne, Steffen, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKruse, Joseph A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLudewig, Anna-Dorothea, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLühe, Irmela von der, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPeitsch, Helmut, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPufelska, Agnieszka, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchneider, Ulrike, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchoor, Ker